             was indicted for <rs id="t17791020-28-off150" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-off150" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-off150" type="offenceSubcategory" value="grandLarceny"></interp>
               stealing 61 b. of moist sugar, value 2 s. the property of persons unknown
            </rs>, <rs id="t17791020-28-cd151" type="crimeDate">October 18th</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791020-28-off150 t17791020-28-cd151"></join>.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17791020-28-person337">
                  ROBERT
                   LAMBERT
               <interp inst="t17791020-28-person337" type="surname" value="LAMBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-person337" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-person337" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I saw the prisoner go to the buildings at <placeName id="t17791020-28-crimeloc152">Fox-quay</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17791020-28-crimeloc152" type="placeName" value="Fox-quay"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17791020-28-crimeloc152" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791020-28-off150 t17791020-28-crimeloc152"></join>, on the 19th of this month; when he came out I examined him, and found six pounds of sugar in his pocket; he worked with us as a <rs id="t17791020-28-deflabel153" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17791020-28-defend336 t17791020-28-deflabel153"></join> for a quarter of a year together. I never knew him dishonest before. This was on a general festival, St. Luke's day; he was not quite sober; he cried and said that during his service he had never been guilty of any thing before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17791020-28-person338">
                  JOHN
                   BULLER
               <interp inst="t17791020-28-person338" type="surname" value="BULLER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-person338" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-person338" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am employed at Fox-quay as a supervisor. I never knew any thing against the prisoner before; this was on Horn-fair day; the work was over; he came down out of the warehouse; he was stopped, and six pounds of sugar found upon him; he was in liquor; he desired to pay for the sugar; he said he was persuaded by another soldier to take the sugar.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>A cooper who works there gave me the sugar. I know him only by sight.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="177910200052"></xptr>( The prisoner called his serjeant and another person, who gave him a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17791020-28-verdict154" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17791020-28-verdict154" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the London Jury before Mr. Justice WILLES.</p>
